Given this is a Dart project, I'll write it in Dart:

```dart
/// Validates an email address against RFC 5322 simplified rules.
///
/// Checks structure (local@domain), character validity, and domain format.
/// Intentionally avoids a single mega-regex in favor of readability.
bool isValidEmail(String email) {
  // Split on '@' вҖ” must have exactly one unquoted '@'
  final parts = email.split('@');
  if (parts.length != 2) return false;

  final local = parts[0];
  final domain = parts[1];

  // Local part: 1-64 chars, alphanumeric + allowed specials, no leading/trailing dots
  if (local.isEmpty || local.length > 64) return false;
  if (local.startsWith('.') || local.endsWith('.') || local.contains('..')) {
    return false;
  }
  if (!RegExp(r"^[a-zA-Z0-9.!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+$").hasMatch(local)) {
    return false;
  }

  // Domain: 1-253 chars, split into labels separated by dots
  if (domain.isEmpty || domain.length > 253) return false;
  final labels = domain.split('.');
  if (labels.length < 2) return false; // require at least one dot

  for (final label in labels) {
    if (label.isEmpty || label.length > 63) return false;
    if (label.startsWith('-') || label.endsWith('-')) return false;
    if (!RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9-]+$').hasMatch(label)) return false;
  }

  // TLD must not be all-numeric (that would be an IP, which needs brackets)
  if (RegExp(r'^[0-9]+$').hasMatch(labels.last)) return false;

  return true;
}
```

**Design choices worth noting:**

- **No single giant regex.** The classic email regex is 6,000+ characters and still wrong. Breaking validation into structural checks is both more correct and more maintainable.
- **RFC 5322 simplified, not full.** Quoted local parts (`"weird@stuff"@example.com`) are technically valid but essentially never seen in the wild вҖ” supporting them adds complexity with near-zero practical value.
- **The all-numeric TLD check** catches a subtle case: `user@123.456` looks like a domain but is actually a malformed IP literal (which RFC 5321 requires brackets for: `[123.456]`).
- **Length limits are real.** 64-char local, 253-char domain, 63-char labels вҖ” these come from DNS and SMTP specs and catch garbage inputs that a naive regex would accept.
